es%2F98e196b0-ca1d-4662-80c6-e48d8f747be2_1477x800.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">来源： <a href="https://www.csis.org/analysis/green-industrial-policy-holistic-approach">CSIS</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>因此，如果您是美国人，那么您昨天就不会购买中国电动汽车，现在您也不会明天购买。什么都不会改变。</p><p>但这并不意味着这些关税是表现性的。他们是<em>预防性</em>。过去，我们看到了中国突然在美国或其他国家泛滥的某个出口产品的例子，例如<a href="https://twitter.com/Brad_Setser/status/1790236572731781130">挖掘机</a>。拜登的关税将确保电动汽车不会发生这种情况。</p><p>那好还是坏？关税会使美国人的生活更昂贵吗？拜登的举动会促进美国汽车行业吗？它会减慢绿色过渡吗？这对美国贸易政策意味着什么？</p><p>我将尝试回答这些问题。</p><h4>中国电动汽车的关税是否会使美国人的生活更昂贵？</h4><p>这个问题的简短答案是“否”，原因只是上面的图表。美国人没有购买任何中国电动汽车，因此中国电动汽车的价格不仅仅是使美国人为任何东西付出更多。</p><p>现在，关税<em>可能</em>是为了防止未来的廉价Ev Bonanza到达美国的海岸。如果拜登什么也没做，中国可能会以便宜的高品质高品质电动汽车淹没美国。然后，一群对高利率感到压力和杂货价格感到压力的美国人可能能够通过购买便宜的高质量的中国制造的电动汽车来减轻一些缓解。</p><p>中国电动汽车<em>非常</em>好。中国一直在努力制造出良好的内燃机，但向电动汽车的转变使他们完全超越了冰车。由于中国在电池行业中占主导地位，因此掌握电动汽车非常容易。凯文·威廉姆斯（Kevin Williams）有<a href="https://insideevs.com/features/719015/china-is-ahead-of-west/">一篇关于中国电动汽车高质量的文章</a>，尽管它包含相当一部分的手动挥动“我们已经煮熟”等，但您还是应该阅读的。威廉姆斯的结论是：</p><blockquote><p>如果美国和欧洲得到他们想要的东西 - 对中国进口的镇压 - 不会觉得这会带来更好的汽车。感觉这将使这些市场的买家也锁定在没有执行的汽车上。这是赤裸裸的贸易保护主义者，因为深处，所有西方汽车高管以及一些鹰派中国专家都知道，中国电动汽车和PHEV模型比欧洲，其他亚洲和美国品牌提出的更具吸引力。</p></blockquote><p>这是对的。而且有理由担心，如果没有中国进口的竞争压力，通用汽车和福特等人（甚至是特斯拉）的竞争压力将少得多地复制创新的中文功能（例如基于屏幕的控件）的理由。美国消费者最终可能会选择较低的车辆选择。</p><p>但是我认为这不会发生，这是出于一个简单的原因：<em>中国汽车公司不必在中国制造汽车</em>。</p><p>关税是根据良好进行最终组装的位置提出的。因此，如果Byd或其他中国汽车制造商将其工厂放到美国，墨西哥，加拿大或中国以外的任何地方 - 他们仍然可以将电动汽车出售给美国而不会受到Biden的新关税的打击。这<a href="https://www.wsj.com/business/autos/chinese-ev-maker-byd-exploring-mexico-factory-as-entry-to-u-s-market-411360fa">已经在进行中</a>：</p><blockquote><p>中国汽车制造商比德（Byd）将目光投向了墨西哥，因为它寻求<a href="https://www.wsj.com/business/autos/chinas-ev-champion-byd-will-take-on-the-world-in-2024-9da4cfde?mod=article_inline">全球扩张</a>向北美的追求变化……在墨西哥为美国建造汽车将允许汽车制造商避免，如果他们直接从中国派出中国，他们将征收高额进口关税……近年来，至少有十二个中国电动汽车组件供应商宣布了新的工厂或增加了他们在墨西哥的现有投资[。]</p></blockquote><p>墨西哥的中国汽车工厂将能够利用中国的供应链（尤其是电池），降低其成本。他们将通过凯文·威廉姆斯（Kevin Williams）非常喜欢的那些大屏幕界面进行创新的中国设计。他们将结合中国工厂发现的任何集会创新，进一步推动成本。</p><p>因此，美国人仍然能够获得“中国”电动汽车，而不是来自中国工厂。没关系。墨西哥需要工作和收入，美国消费者可以使用一些廉价的未来派汽车，美国汽车公司可以使用竞争对手。</p><p>一个公开的问题是，中国政府将决定在墨西哥的中国拥有的工厂进行补贴。从理论上讲，中国可以部署它用于补贴国内生产的所有相同政策工具 - 税收抵免，廉价贷款，直接付款等，以帮助中国公司从墨西哥工厂抽出便宜的汽车。这是否完全是另一个问题 - 中国政府可能希望在该国保持制造业工作，从而对FDI进行补贴。所以我们拭目以待。</p><p>但是，即使没有补贴，中国公司确实确实制造了便宜的好电动汽车，美国人仍然能够在新的关税制度下掌握它们。</p><p>当然，如果我们还对在墨西哥和其他第三国制造的电动汽车征收关税，这会变得更加困难。实际上，特朗普<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-05-12/biden-s-china-tariffs-salvo-to-range-from-doubling-to-quadruple?sref=R8NfLgwS">已经在威胁到这一点</a>：</p><blockquote><p> [特朗普]警告说，中国公司将尝试在墨西哥制造汽车，然后根据美国 - 墨西哥 - 加拿大协议将其运送到美国，避免关税，特朗普同意该协议作为总统。特朗普说，他将在墨西哥对中国制造的汽车征收200％的关税。</p></blockquote><p>如果将关税扩大到包括墨西哥等第三国，那么美国消费者确实<em>可以</em>被锁定在尖端电动汽车的市场上。到那时，中国汽车公司避免关税的唯一途径就是在美国制造汽车。日本品牌<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/whos-afraid-of-east-asian-management">取得了成功</a>。但是中国公司可能<a href="https://finance.yahoo.com/news/tesla-rival-byd-not-planning-to-come-to-the-us-exec-says-212306507.html?guccounter=1&amp;guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&amp;guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAFivsL7qUpNWPP-cfSUt0j5PQUm5ibp_ujyWm-kg_RkaeAezjzATUNk5iISI6OHDIinXzOht6YxPy0KUwSFUs43kSdE2icPp73w0HmjLGO0NXM4BpSHDCG1ljf2gKLHRF81dm56VNwjE2MjyQRqPMtfQyQykGiOIu4q_H_D_emgM">不愿这样做</a>，或者他们的政府可能阻止他们这样做。所以我们拭目以待。</p><h4>关税对美国汽车行业意味着什么？</h4><p>拜登的关税将为我们的汽车公司和福特等汽车公司提供暂时的缓刑。但除非拜登或未来的特朗普总统也对墨西哥制造的电动汽车征收关税，否则这种喘息的时间将是短暂的，因为通用汽车和福特仍将在国内市场面临来自中国汽车制造商的品牌竞争。</p><p>这场比赛不仅打击了通用汽车和福特的新生电动汽车业务 - 它将打击他们的整个业务。冰车和电动汽车正处于直接竞争。从长远来看，有几种有利于电动汽车的结构性因素。这些包括：</p><ol><li><p>政府为加速绿色过渡的努力</p></li><li><p>冰技术基本上停滞不前，电池技术正在飞跃和界限进步</p></li><li><p>由于缩放效果，每年电池成本都会下降这一事实（主要来自中国）</p></li><li><p>家庭充电</p></li></ol><p>去年，我写了一篇文章，认为电动汽车注定要取代冰车，而变化将很快发生： </p><div class="digest-post-embed" data-attrs="{&quot;nodeId&quot;:&quot;adb2e3b8-f401-46dd-84b3-d3cf2bc49805&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;It&#8217;s time for another techno-optimist post! Instead of an as-yet-unproven technology like green hydrogen or battery-powered appliances, today&#8217;s post is about a technology that&#8217;s already taking over the world: battery electric vehicles, commonly known as EVs.&quot;,&quot;size&quot;:&quot;sm&quot;,&quot;isEditorNode&quot;:true,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;All the arguments against EVs are wrong&quot;,&quot;publishedBylines&quot;:[{&quot;id&quot;:8243895,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Noah Smith&quot;,&quot;bio&quot;:&quot;Econ blogger&quot;,&quot;photo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/89fd964a-586f-461a-9f5a-ea4587d45728_397x441.png&quot;,&quot;is_guest&quot;:false,&quot;bestseller_tier&quot;:10000}],&quot;post_date&quot;:&quot;2023-05-14T07:05:30.107Z&quot;,&quot;cover_image&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6ef19f80-7aea-45fd-be51-18fa1416f9f9_1166x773.jpeg&quot;,&quot;cover_image_alt&quot;:null,&quot;canonical_url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/all-the-arguments-against-evs-are&quot;,&quot;section_name&quot;:null,&quot;id&quot;:121266134,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;newsletter&quot;,&quot;reaction_count&quot;:449,&quot;comment_count&quot;:393,&quot;publication_name&quot;:&quot;Noahpinion&quot;,&quot;publication_logo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F04281755-2cd6-42e5-a496-e69153abebb2_281x281.png&quot;,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true}"></div><p>与电动汽车不同，冰车必须经常填充，电动汽车在人们的车库里过夜，因此只需要长途旅行。因此，冰车需要密集的加油站网络才能可行。随着电动汽车开始接管市场，冰车变得稀少，我们现有的许多加油站将倒闭。这将使拥有冰车变得不方便，这将加速向电动汽车的转变。冲洗并重复。一旦此过程开始，汽油动力的汽车将很快成为利基产品，而电动汽车将成为大多数人驾驶的汽车。</p><p>现在，这还没有发生。美国电动汽车的市场仍在增加，但不如许多人预期的快速，因此，美国汽车制造商正在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/business/autos/general-motors-gm-q3-earnings-report-2023-5064f4c2">扩大其电动汽车计划</a>。</p><p>但是，大多数美国人（除了将绿色技术变成文化战争的保守派的坚硬核心之外）期望在不远的未来获得电动汽车： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg" width="800" height="418" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:418,&quot;width&quot;:800,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:65632,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb7582636-15e9-426f-b75a-d97c2bb949f3_800x418.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源： <a href="https://www.sustainabilitybynumbers.com/p/american-attitudes-ev?utm_source=post-email-title&amp;publication_id=1199196&amp;post_id=143703245&amp;utm_campaign=email-post-title&amp;isFreemail=true&amp;r=4wp13&amp;triedRedirect=true&amp;utm_medium=email">汉娜·里奇（Hannah Ritchie）</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>如果通用汽车和福特缩减其产品的规模，如果特斯拉专注于机器人而不是新的更好的电动汽车，那么很有可能美国公司在墨西哥建造汽车进行美国电动汽车革命。关税不会阻止这一点，除非a）我们对墨西哥和任何其他国家征收类似的关税，而b）中国汽车公司拒绝在美国建造工厂</p><p>而且还有其他美国关税<em>无法</em>停止的事情：美国汽车公司在出口市场中遇到了兴趣。</p><p>福特<a href="https://stockdividendscreener.com/auto-manufacturers/ford-global-vehicle-sales-and-market-share/">从北美</a>赚了大部分资金，但通用汽车在亚洲的收入和<a href="https://www.statista.com/statistics/314759/revenue-of-tesla-by-region/">特斯拉的</a><a href="https://stockdividendscreener.com/auto-manufacturers/general-motors-vehicle-sales-and-market-share/">收入尽可能多</a>。美国关税显然不适用于将中国电动汽车出售给越南，日本，澳大利亚或其他任何地方，因此他们绝对不会采取任何行动来帮助我们在主要的国外市场上竞争。许多其他国家不太可能对中国电动汽车构成巨大的拜登风格的关税，因此通用汽车和福特和特斯拉将面对比德和其他中国汽车制造商在海外或无所不包的竞争环境中（除了在中国本身外，政府将在那里倾斜秤，而倾向于自己的国内品牌）。</p><p>因此，中国竞争可能会将美国和其他汽车公司赶出世界市场。这将加剧现有趋势： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg" width="836" height="471" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:471,&quot;width&quot;:836,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:164754,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2276de26-a108-4dcf-beb5-ba94726f5c8e_836x471.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源： <a href="https://stockdividendscreener.com/auto-manufacturers/general-motors-vehicle-sales-and-market-share/">StockDividendScreener.com</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>因此，美国汽车公司（例如欧洲，日本和韩国汽车公司）正处于严重的危险之中，关税或没有。电动汽车过渡正在发生，中国是电动汽车的最好的。除非他们可以举起比赛，否则用凯文·威廉姆斯（Kevin Williams）的话来说，他们是“煮熟的”。</p><h4> Will the tariffs slow down the green transition?</h4><p> A lot of people are worried that tariffs like these will slow down the transition to a low-carbon future powered by solar power and batteries. For example, <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2024-03-17/trade-wars-bans-on-evs-and-solar-panels-are-not-the-answer?sref=R8NfLgwS">David Fickling writes</a> :</p><blockquote><p> China&#39;s widening lead in clean technology, coupled with its vast trade surplus…are combining with faltering efforts on decarbonization in developed countries to produce a toxic mix…If green technology such as electric vehicles…gets badged as foreign and threatening and finds itself excluded via…tariff policies, then drastically falling costs aren&#39;t going to be enough to get it into the hands of consumers…An acceleration in trade wars will only slow our path to zero [carbon].</p></blockquote><p> He&#39;s right to worry. Transportation is responsible for <a href="https://www.epa.gov/ghgemissions/sources-greenhouse-gas-emissions">almost 30% of US carbon emissions</a> , or about 4% of the global total. If the US failed to switch to EVs, it could hamper decarbonization efforts by a small but noticeable amount.</p><p> Now, as I said before, if tariffs are only placed on EVs made in China, there&#39;s not much to worry about here. Americans will still switch to EVs, they&#39;ll just buy their Chinese-brand EVs from factories in Mexico. The green transition will continue apace.</p><p>不过，如果美国对<em>所有</em>外国电动汽车征收关税，我们可能会遇到麻烦。 A refusal of GM and Ford to bet big on the EV transition (and Tesla&#39;s pivot to robotaxis) would then be able to keep America as a gas-guzzling nation, clinging to our outmoded comfort cars, orphaned from global technology and locked out of the high-tech future.</p><p> And if Republicans turn EVs into a culture war the way they&#39;ve done with <a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/florida-alabama-lab-grown-mean-ban-2024/">lab-grown meat</a> , they could enact restrictive state-level policies that would slow the transition even further.</p><p> So I am worried about the green transition in the US, though that worry depends very strongly on whether the US extends its tariffs to Mexican-made EVs.</p><h4> What does this mean for trade policy going forward?</h4><p> The most important thing about these tariffs is probably the message they send. Protectionism is now the consensus economic policy of both major political parties in the United States. Biden has extended the Trump tariffs on China and levied the new EV tariffs; Trump is <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-05-12/biden-s-china-tariffs-salvo-to-range-from-doubling-to-quadruple?sref=R8NfLgwS">trying to one-up Biden</a> by promising to raise the 100% tariffs to 200%, extend them to Mexico, and slap an additional 60% tariff on all Chinese-made goods. There is currently no major party or presidential candidate that you can vote for in America that is even remotely interested in free trade.</p><p> But that still leaves lots of questions. Most importantly, there&#39;s the question of what, exactly, protectionism is trying to <em>protect</em> . I see four main potential purposes of tariffs:</p><ol><li><p> Protecting auto industry jobs and/or corporate profits</p></li><li><p> Reducing trade imbalances with China</p></li><li><p> Eliminating security risks from Chinese hacking</p></li><li><p> Protecting domestic defense manufacturing capacity</p></li></ol><p> The first of these is probably foremost in the minds of many progressives, and possibly Trump as well. On the plus side, if Chinese car companies could be persuaded to put their factories in the US like Japanese car companies did, labor-protectionists would be happy. GM and Ford would still be mad, and they&#39;d probably have some supporters in Congress, but the prospect of a whole bunch of good American manufacturing jobs in BYD or Geely factories would probably win out.</p><p> The second of these — reducing trade imbalances — is what everyone talks about. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/world/china/china-shock-2-0-sparks-global-backlash-against-flood-of-cheap-goods-d394238b">Articles about the Second China Shock</a> usually mention things like Chinese underconsumption, overcapacity, and trade imbalances. The Rhodium Group has a report called “ <a href="https://rhg.com/research/overcapacity-at-the-gate/">Overcapacity at the Gates</a> ” that sums up the viewpoint well. The two most well-known commentators on this issue — or at least, the two I read the most — are <a href="https://twitter.com/Brad_Setser">Brad Setser</a> and <a href="https://twitter.com/michaelxpettis">Michael Pettis</a> , so if you want to learn more about this idea, check them out.</p><p> It&#39;s not clear whether trade imbalances by themselves are a legitimate concern, or whether they&#39;re a catch-all proxy for concerns about jobs and other issues. It&#39;s also not clear whether tariffs can restore trade balance — it&#39;s possible that the expensive dollar is to blame, and that only an abdication of the dollar&#39;s role as the global reserve currency can fix things. More on that in a post coming soon. But for right now, what&#39;s clear is that many people are upset about trade imbalances, and tariffs are one available policy for trying to address those imbalances.</p><p> The third issue — security risks from Chinese-made goods — is something I&#39;m not really qualified to assess. The fear is that if China&#39;s security services put backdoors in Chinese-made products, they could use those built-in vulnerabilities <a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/biden-administration-will-investigate-national-security-risks-posed-ch-rcna141099">to cause havoc in the US</a> in the event of a war:</p><blockquote><p> Commerce Secretary Gina Raimondo said connected cars “are like smart phones on wheels” and pose a serious national security risk.</p><p> “These vehicles are connected to the internet. They collect huge amounts of sensitive data on the drivers — personal information, biometric information, where the car goes,&#39;&#39; she told reporters late Wednesday…</p><p> Data collection is not the only concern, she and other officials said. Connected vehicles could also be remotely enabled or manipulated by bad actors.</p><p> “Imagine if there were thousands or hundreds of thousands of Chinese-connected vehicles on American roads that could be immediately and simultaneously disabled by somebody in Beijing,&#39;&#39; Raimondo said. “So it&#39;s scary to contemplate the cyber risks, espionage risks that these pose.&#39;&#39;</p></blockquote><p> Given how a single wayward cargo ship just <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Scott_Key_Bridge_collapse">took out a major bridge</a> in Baltimore that will take years to repair, it&#39;s pretty terrifying to think about how much destruction China could wreak if it controlled all of our cars.</p><p> I will say, though, that it seems like the danger here is entirely from Chinese-made <em>computer chips</em> . A GM or Ford car made with Chinese computer chips has the same vulnerability as a BYD car made with those same chips. So if you&#39;re worried about cybersecurity, it seems to me that the one and only thing you need to keep out of the US are Chinese-made semiconductors.</p><p> Anyway, this brings us to the final concern: defense manufacturing capacity. In times of war, civilian factories are typically repurposed to make war materiel — for example, when Ford <a href="https://www.assemblymag.com/articles/94614-how-fords-willow-run-assembly-plant-helped-win-world-war-ii">churned out massive quantities</a> of B-24 bombers during World War 2. We have a law, called the Defense Production Act, that allows the government to order US companies to switch their production lines to make military equipment or other goods critical to national security (for example, we used the DPA to make companies build ventilators during Covid).</p><p> But the DPA is useless if you <em>don&#39;t have the factories</em> to repurpose. If US heavy manufacturing withers and dies in the face of Chinese competition, the US won&#39;t be able to add much to its defense production capacity in a war. That could lead to a swift and devastating US defeat at the hands of China.</p><p> My guess is that China knows this very well, and that this is one reason it has been so generous with subsidies and so gung-ho about ramping up manufacturing exports. Yes, of course they want jobs and growth, but the tantalizing potential of forcibly deindustrializing the West through subsidized exports has undoubtedly crossed the minds of every Chinese leader.</p><p> So in order to have domestic manufacturing available for military repurposing, it&#39;s probably necessary to erect trade barriers to protect against massively subsidized Chinese import surges. This consideration has nothing to do with American jobs or profits or trade deficits — it&#39;s just a cold, hard military reality. Opponents of protectionism — the Cato Institute, the writers at <a href="https://www.economist.com/briefing/2024/05/09/the-worlds-economic-order-is-breaking-down">The Economist</a> , and so on — seem to have no alternative answer here.</p><p> In other words, there are multiple intersecting reasons for tariffs to go up, and most off these have bipartisan appeal. Biden&#39;s big tariffs on Chinese EVs are likely only the start of a major shift in America&#39;s trade policy. </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-big-tariffs-are-here?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-big-tariffs-are-here?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p><p></p>; 
How I would regulate AIFocus on the choke points in the process by which AI could do harm.https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/how-i-would-regulate-ai https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/how-i-would-regulate-aiNoah Smith Mon, 13 May 2024 07:48:22 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg" width="680" height="680" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1024,&quot;width&quot;:1024,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:680,&quot;bytes&quot;:62463,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff4fc0200-1bb1-4640-bcde-5dd9172d3d57_1024x1024.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line><figcaption class="image-caption"> Art by GPT-4</figcaption></figure></div><p> I thought I&#39;d take a break from writing about weighty matters like trade wars and presidential elections, and talk about something more whimsical and lighthearted — how to keep quasi-sentient computers from taking all our jobs and then hunting us to extinction with swarms of autonomous drones!</p><p> Well, OK, I don&#39;t think we&#39;re going to be <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/llms-are-not-going-to-destroy-the">facing off with Skynet</a> anytime soon. But generative AI is undeniably a very powerful new technology, and the list of powerful new technologies that the human race hasn&#39;t used for destructive purposes is very short indeed. So it probably makes sense to start thinking about how to use regulation to decrease the likelihood that AI will be used to cause catastrophes.</p><p> That&#39;s a lot easier said than done, however. It&#39;s very hard to predict what kind of regulation would make a technology safer <em>before</em> the harms materialize, and it&#39;s very easy to create regulation that slows down technological progress. So <em>a priori</em> , a fairly likely outcome of AI regulation is that AI progress slows down, but AI still ends up causing harm in ways that the regulators never anticipated.</p><p> Realizing this basic difficulty, the Biden administration wisely taking a light touch — at least in the US There was some speculation that <a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/10/30/fact-sheet-president-biden-issues-executive-order-on-safe-secure-and-trustworthy-artificial-intelligence/">Biden&#39;s executive order</a> on AI last October would focus on limiting AI capabilities. But instead, the order&#39;s main protection against existential risk is simply a mandate for safety testing on foundational models (like ChatGPT and Gemini). It also has provisions to protect against the non-existential risks of AI — job displacement, deepfakes, erosion of privacy, and so on.</p><p> Other attempts currently in the pipeline would go farther, however. California legislators are proposing a bunch of <a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1axh0K__Wx6Sy2Gi9atYNT8l0du0w5AuffNYkrVszJSU/edit#gid=644486299">state-level AI safety bills</a> . One of these is State Senator Scott Wiener&#39;s <a href="https://sd11.senate.ca.gov/news/20240208-senator-wiener-introduces-legislation-ensure-safe-development-large-scale-artificial">SB 1047</a> , which would impose <a href="https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billNavClient.xhtml?bill_id=202320240SB1047">a whole bunch of safety requirements</a> on companies building foundational models. If the models are found to cause major havoc, the bill would hold companies liable for some portion of the costs.</p><p> I am no expert on AI technology, but I wonder if regulations like this can actually be implemented as written. SB 1047 要求人工智能公司在模型接受数据训练<em>之前</em>了解其模型可以做和不能做的各种事情。 As far as I know, that&#39;s not even possible; you don&#39;t really know what a model can do before it&#39;s trained. In fact, even after a model like ChatGPT is trained, it seems impossible to really know what dangerous stuff it could be used to do. Does anyone think we know, right now, whether GPT-4 is actually capable of causing catastrophic harm, in the hands of the right villain?我不这么认为。 And GPT-4 has been out for over a year now; when we&#39;re talking about <em>new</em> models, we&#39;ll have even less knowledge to go on.</p><p> So I think bills like SB 1047 that require AI companies to make all sorts of safety claims about their models will mostly result in the companies making BS claims of total and complete safety, which no one will be able to verify one way or the other.</p><p> I don&#39;t think regulations like these are going to slow down AI innovation much, but I also don&#39;t think they&#39;re going to do a lot to limit real risks from AI — mostly because AI companies are already trying hard to limit those risks on their own. In fact, I&#39;m not sure if <em>anything</em> can eliminate those risks, since generative AI is kind of a black box, and since it&#39;s very hard to know what it&#39;s capable of. But I do have a few ideas about how to go about regulating AI effectively, in ways that wouldn&#39;t spam companies with red tape.</p><h4> Reserve resources for human use</h4><p> I&#39;ll talk about some ideas about how to mitigate existential risk from AI — the “Skynet” scenario and things like that. But first I want to talk about what kind of regulation might limit <em>economic</em> risk. A whole lot of people are scared of AI displacing people from their jobs, and many worry that our species could even become economically obsolete like horses. But I think there is one simple regulation that could prevent this outcome.</p><p><a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/how-i-would-regulate-ai">阅读更多</a></p>; 
The death (again) of the internet as we know itA few big changes are making the online world a more boring place to hang out. https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-death-again-of-the-internet-as https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-death-again-of-the-internet-asNoah Smith Sat, 11 May 2024 23:43:35 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ffe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.jpeg" width="710" height="710" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/fe795b6d-eaa0-4806-8eb9-cd5afcdf2443_1024x1024.j